node.text: Rio De Janeiro, Brazil: Witness the inspiring story of Tuany, a 23-year-old ballet dancer who started a dance company for young girls in the middle of one of Rio De Janeiro’s most dangerous favelas. She gives students hope for a better future and a safe space away from the violent world around them.

node.text: Grand Caillou/Dulac, Louisiana, U.S.A.: Meet Chief Shirell, the first female chief of her southern Louisiana tribe. Her ancestors have lived on the land for hundreds of years, and they are now expected to be among the United States’ first climate refugees. Chief Shirell can’t stop the storms, but she is impacting the legacy of her ancestors, the lives of her community today and the future of her people.

node.text: Memphis, Tennessee, U.S.A.: Meet Kayla, who has dedicated her life to helping homeless transgender women of color in Memphis, Tennessee. Having experienced homelessness and violence herself, Kayla has created a safe community for these notoriously discriminated-against people. She is building more than two dozen houses across Memphis for transgender women who need safety and a place to call home.

node.text: Photo by @tamaramerino_photography / Adherents of the Aghori cult carry a human skull, in Varanasi, India. Called a kapala, it's used as a bowl from which to eat, drink, and perform rituals. They say it reminds them that everything is beautiful and pure. An Aghori is said to be a master of spiritual power, able to cure mental and physical ailments alike. Since the 5th century B.C., the Aghori have followed the path of Shiva, the Hindu god of destruction, believing that he resides in cremation grounds, where they live. They consume human flesh for some rituals—from corpses routinely found floating in the Ganges—and immerse themselves in environments where death surrounds them as part of their daily routine. Despite their extreme practices and lifestyle, a true Aghori will never hurt another being. Follow me on @tamaramerino_photography to see the full story. #aghori #cult

Photo by @simonnorfolkstudio / The moniker "Afghanistan,  graveyard of empires" has never seemed so true as when watching headlines of the catastrophic bomb attack and shambolic withdrawal in Kabul. I've been photographing the ruins of great empires within its borders since 2001. Here, from December of that year, a former teahouse stands next to the wreckage of the old Soviet-era exhibition space in Kabul. Just a few months earlier, balloons were illegal under Taliban rule. Follow me @simonnorfolkstudio for updates, outtakes, unpublished and archive material. 
#afghanistan #Kabul #afghanistaned #battlefield #war #taliban

Photos and video by David Chancellor @chancellordavid | Four elephant bulls rise out of the Chobe River, in Botswana. I watched them stand on the bank at the river's edge, each one stepping forward and assessing the crossing, then moving back to be absorbed into the coalition. Finally, the moment came when the opportunity for fresh browse outweighed the uncertainty, and the lead bull stepped forward, tasted the water with his trunk, emptied the remainder over his back, and began the process that the others would follow. For a good while, all one could see of them was the tops of their heads and trunks—now being used as snorkels. Slowly, the mass made its way across 
like a great river monster. Then they rose as one from the water, transformed by the evening light into magnificent brass sculptures. As they moved from water to land again, I couldn’t help thinking that within such things lies the cure of evils; after witnessing such incredible beauty, surely it becomes impossible to manifest evil upon such extraordinary beings. From an ongoing story "Botswana’s elephant politics." To see more follow me @chancellordavid.

Photo by @stevewinterphoto / What happens when mother and daughter square off in the wild? This image shows two female leopards staring each other down. I suspect it's a mom and daughter. Female big cats are philopatric: Daughters stay near the area where they were born and take a piece of mom's home range. They have a low tolerance for each other and are fiercely territorial. If you were to look at the savanna where they live from a bird's-eye view, you'd see leopard females living in a cluster of females that are largely related—moms, aunts, daughters, sisters. Male leopards are completely different,  traveling hundreds if not thousands of kilometers to find their own homes. Follow me @stevewinterphoto for more big cat shots from around the world.
#leopard #cat #bigcat#catsofinstagram #catfight #fight#daughter #mother #sisterhood

node.text: Photo by @acacia.johnson / The last rays of sunset cast a brilliant alpenglow on the peaks of Spitsbergen, Svalbard. This archipelago, located about halfway between Norway and the North Pole, is a haven for Arctic wildlife such as polar bears, seals, and walrus. But temperatures in Svalbard are rising at five times the global average. Until only a few years ago, stable sea ice lined Spitsbergen's west coast until May each year. Now, much of the ice is melting as early as March—when this image was taken aboard the deck of an expedition ship, traveling through open water. Follow me at @acacia.johnson for more from the Arctic and beyond. #svalbard #norway #arctic #climatechange

Reteti is the first ever community-owned elephant sanctuary in Africa. The orphans arrive at the sanctuary as a result of human-elephant conflict, climate-related issues, and some rare cases of poaching, where they are nursed back to health by dedicated keepers and later released back to the wild.

node.text: Photo by @mattiasklumofficial / In Tanzania, a pack of African painted dogs devour a young kudu. The dogs are very social, and packs frequently share food and assist ill or weak family members. Intricate social interactions are common; the dogs communicate by touch, vocalization, and action. African wild dogs are endangered, and faced with shrinking room to roam. They are also quite susceptible to diseases spread by domestic animals. She's in a hut located about two kilometers (just over a mile) outside Ny-Ålesund, a research station in the Svalbard archipelago. Resident scientists can use small huts located around town during their leisure time. Susana and her friends gather here weekly for landscape painting sessions.
